# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gvisor-sandbox
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] A third-party source-to-source compiler, GopherJS, transpiles Go to JavaScript for front-end web development.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Go was designed at Google in 2007 to improve programming productivity in an era of multicore, networked machines and large codebases.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Its designers were primarily motivated by their shared dislike of C++.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Go was publicly announced in November 2009, and version 1.0 was released in March 2012.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Go is widely used in production at Google and in many other organizations and open-source projects.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] In retrospect the Go authors judged Go to be successful due to the overall engineering work around the language, including the runtime support for the language's concurrency feature.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] The gopher mascot was introduced in 2009 for the open source launch of the language.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Renée French, who had designed the rabbit mascot for Plan 9, adapted the gopher from an earlier WFMU T-shirt design.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] In November 2016, the Go and Go Mono fonts were released by type designers Charles Bigelow and Kris Holmes specifically for use by the Go project.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Go is a humanist sans-serif resembling Lucida Grande, and Go Mono is monospaced.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Both fonts adhere to the WGL4 character set and were designed to be legible with a large x-height and distinct letterforms.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Both Go and Go Mono adhere to the DIN 1450 standard by having a slashed zero, lowercase `i` with a tail, and an uppercase `I` with serifs.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] In April 2018, the original logo was redesigned by brand designer Adam Smith.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] The new logo is a modern, stylized GO slanting right with trailing streamlines.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] The lack of support for generic programming in initial versions of Go drew considerable criticism.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] The designers expressed an openness to generic programming and noted that built-in functions *were* in fact type-generic, but are treated as special cases; Pike called this a weakness that might be changed at some point.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] The Google team built at least one compiler for an experimental Go dialect with generics, but did not release it.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] In August 2018, the Go principal contributors published draft designs for generic programming and error handling and asked users to submit feedback.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] However, the error handling proposal was eventually abandoned.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] In June 2020, a new draft design document was published that would add the necessary syntax to Go for declaring generic functions and types.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] A code translation tool, *go2go*, was provided to allow users to try the new syntax, along with a generics-enabled version of the online Go Playground.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Generics were finally added to Go in version 1.18 on March 15, 2022.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Go 1 guarantees compatibility for the language specification and major parts of the standard library.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] All versions up through the current Go 1.26 release have maintained this promise.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Go uses a `go1.[major].[patch]` versioning format, such as `go1.26.0` and each major Go release is supported until there are two newer major releases.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Unlike most software, Go calls the second number in a version the major, i.e., in `go1.26.0` the `26` is the major version.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] This is because Go plans to never reach 2.0, prioritizing backwards compatibility over potential breaking changes.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Go is influenced by C (especially the Plan 9 dialect), but with an emphasis on greater simplicity and safety.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Go's syntax includes changes from C aimed at keeping code concise and readable.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] A combined declaration/initialization operator was introduced that allows the programmer to write `i := 3` or `s := "Hello, world!"`, without specifying the types of variables used.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] This contrasts with C's `int i = 3;` and `char *s = "Hello, world!";` (though since C23 type inference has been supported using `auto`, like C++).
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Go also removes the requirement to use parentheses in `if` statement conditions.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Semicolons still terminate statements; but are implicit when the end of a line occurs.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Methods may return multiple values, and returning a `result, err` pair is the conventional way a method indicates an error to its caller in Go.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Go adds literal syntaxes for initializing struct parameters by name and for initializing maps and slices.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] As an alternative to C's three-statement `for` loop, Go's `range` expressions allow concise iteration over arrays, slices, strings, maps, and channels.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Go has a number of built-in types, including numeric ones (`byte`, `int64`, `float32`, etc.), Booleans, and byte strings (`string`).
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Strings are immutable; built-in operators and keywords (rather than functions) provide concatenation, comparison, and UTF-8 encoding/decoding.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Record types can be defined with the `struct` keyword.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Note that `byte` is an alias for `uint8` and `rune` is an alias for `int32`.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] For each type `T` and each non-negative integer constant `n`, there is an array type denoted `[n]T`; arrays of differing lengths are thus of different types.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Dynamic arrays are available as "slices", denoted `[]T` for some type `T` (compare to other languages like C/C++ and Java, where instead the arrays are denoted `T[]`) These have a length and a *capacity* specifying when new memory needs to be allocated to expand the array.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Several slices may share their underlying memory.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] For a pair of types `K`, `V`, the type `map[K]V` is the type mapping type-`K` keys to type-`V` values, which can be thought of as equivalent to `Map<K, V>` in other languages.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] The Go Programming Language specification does not give any performance guarantees or implementation requirements for map types, though it is usually implemented as a hash table (equivalent to `HashMap<K, V>` in other languages).
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Hash tables are built into the language, with special syntax and built-in functions.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] `chan T` is a *channel* that allows sending values of type `T` between concurrent Go processes.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Aside from its support for interfaces, Go's type system is nominal: the `type` keyword can be used to define a new *named type*, which is distinct from other named types that have the same layout (in the case of a `struct`, the same members in the same order).
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Some conversions between types (e.g., between the various integer types) are pre-defined and adding a new type may define additional conversions, but conversions between named types must always be invoked explicitly.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] With this type definition, `ipv4addr(x)` interprets the `uint32` value `x` as an IP address.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Simply assigning `x` to a variable of type `ipv4addr` is a type error.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Any named type has a method set associated with it.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Due to nominal typing, this method definition adds a method to `ipv4addr`, but not on `uint32`.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] While methods have special definition and call syntax, there is no distinct method type.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Go provides two features that replace class inheritance.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] The first is *embedding*, which can be viewed as an automated form of composition.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] The second are its *interfaces*, which provides runtime polymorphism.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Interfaces are a class of types and provide a limited form of structural typing in the otherwise nominal type system of Go.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] An object which is of an interface type is also of another type, much like C++ objects being simultaneously of a base and derived class.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] The design of Go interfaces was inspired by protocols from the Smalltalk programming language.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Multiple sources use the term duck typing when describing Go interfaces.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Although the term duck typing is not precisely defined and therefore not wrong, it usually implies that type conformance is not statically checked.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Because conformance to a Go interface is checked statically by the Go compiler (except when performing a type assertion), the Go authors prefer the term *structural typing*.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] The definition of an interface type lists required methods by name and type.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Any object of type T for which functions exist matching all the required methods of interface type I is an object of type I as well.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] The definition of type T need not (and cannot) identify type I.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] then both a `Square` and a `Circle` are implicitly a `Shape` and can be assigned to a `Shape`-typed variable.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] In formal language, Go's interface system provides structural rather than nominal typing.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Interfaces can embed other interfaces with the effect of creating a combined interface that is satisfied by exactly the types that implement the embedded interface and any methods that the newly defined interface adds.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] The Go standard library uses interfaces to provide genericity in several places, including the input/output system that is based on the concepts of `Reader` and `Writer`.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Besides calling methods via interfaces, Go allows converting interface values to other types with a run-time type check.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] The *empty interface* `interface{}` is an important base case because it can refer to an item of *any* concrete type.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] It is similar to the `Object` class in Java or C# or `void*` in C or `Any` in C++ and Rust and is satisfied by any type, including built-in types like `int`.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Code using the empty interface cannot simply call methods (or built-in operators) on the referred-to object, but it can store the `interface{}` value, try to convert it to a more useful type via a type assertion or type switch, or inspect it with Go's `reflect` package.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Because `interface{}` can refer to any value, it is a limited way to escape the restrictions of static typing, like `void*` in C but with additional run-time type checks.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] The `interface{}` type can be used to model structured data of any arbitrary schema in Go, such as JSON or YAML data, by representing it as a `map[string]interface{}` (map of string to empty interface).
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] This recursively describes data in the form of a dictionary with string keys and values of any type.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Interface values are implemented using pointer to data and a second pointer to run-time type information.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Like some other types implemented using pointers in Go, interface values are `nil` if uninitialized.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Since version 1.18, Go supports generic code using parameterized types.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Functions and types now have the ability to be generic using type parameters.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] These type parameters are specified within square brackets, right after the function or type name.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] The compiler transforms the generic function or type into non-generic by substituting *type arguments* for the type parameters provided, either explicitly by the user or type inference by the compiler.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] This transformation process is referred to as type instantiation.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Interfaces now can define a set of types (known as type set) using `|` (Union) operator, as well as a set of methods.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] These changes were made to support type constraints in generics code.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] For a generic function or type, a constraint can be thought of as the type of the type argument: a meta-type.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] This new `~T` syntax will be the first use of `~` as a token in Go.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] `~T` means the set of all types whose underlying type is `T`.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Go uses the `iota` identifier to create enumerated constants.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] In Go's package system, each package has a path (e.g., `"compress/bzip2"` or `"golang.org/x/net/html"`) and a name (e.g., `bzip2` or `html`).
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] By default other packages' definitions must *always* be prefixed with the other package's name.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] However the name used can be changed from the package name, and if imported as `_`, then no package prefix is required.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Only the *capitalized* names from other packages are accessible: `io.Reader` is public but `bzip2.reader` is not.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] The Go language has built-in facilities, as well as library support, for writing concurrent programs.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] The runtime is asynchronous: program execution that performs, for example, a network read will be suspended until data is available to process, allowing other parts of the program to perform other work.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] This is built into the runtime and does not require any changes in program code.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] The go runtime also automatically schedules concurrent operations (goroutines) across multiple CPUs; this can achieve parallelism for a properly written program.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] The primary concurrency construct is the *goroutine*, a type of green thread.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] A function call prefixed with the `go` keyword starts a function in a new goroutine.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] While a standard library package featuring most of the classical concurrency control structures (mutex locks, etc.) is available, idiomatic concurrent programs instead prefer *channels*, which send messages between goroutines.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Optional buffers store messages in FIFO order and allow sending goroutines to proceed before their messages are received.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Channels are typed, so that a channel of type `chan T` can only be used to transfer messages of type `T`.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Special syntax is used to operate on them; `<-ch` is an expression that causes the executing goroutine to block until a value comes in over the channel `ch`, while `ch <- x` sends the value `x` (possibly blocking until another goroutine receives the value).
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] The built-in `switch`-like `select` statement can be used to implement non-blocking communication on multiple channels; see below for an example.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Go has a memory model describing how goroutines must use channels or other operations to safely share data.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] The existence of channels does not by itself set Go apart from actor model-style concurrent languages like Erlang, where messages are addressed directly to actors (corresponding to goroutines).
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] In the actor model, channels are themselves actors, therefore addressing a channel just means to address an actor.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] The actor style can be simulated in Go by maintaining a one-to-one correspondence between goroutines and channels, but the language allows multiple goroutines to share a channel or a single goroutine to send and receive on multiple channels.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] From these tools one can build concurrent constructs like worker pools, pipelines (in which, say, a file is decompressed and parsed as it downloads), background calls with timeout, "fan-out" parallel calls to a set of services, and others.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Channels have also found uses further from the usual notion of interprocess communication, like serving as a concurrency-safe list of recycled buffers, implementing coroutines (which helped inspire the name *goroutine*), and implementing iterators.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Concurrency-related structural conventions of Go (channels and alternative channel inputs) are derived from Tony Hoare's communicating sequential processes model.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Unlike previous concurrent programming languages such as Occam or Limbo (a language on which Go co-designer Rob Pike worked), Go does not provide any built-in notion of safe or verifiable concurrency.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] While the communicating-processes model is favored in Go, it is not the only one: all goroutines in a program share a single address space.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] This means that mutable objects and pointers can be shared between goroutines; see § Lack of data race safety, below.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Although Go's concurrency features are not aimed primarily at parallel processing, they can be used to program shared-memory multi-processor machines.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Various studies have been done into the effectiveness of this approach.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] One of these studies compared the size (in lines of code) and speed of programs written by a seasoned programmer not familiar with the language and corrections to these programs by a Go expert (from Google's development team), doing the same for Chapel, Cilk and Intel TBB.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] The study found that the non-expert tended to write divide-and-conquer algorithms with one `go` statement per recursion, while the expert wrote distribute-work-synchronize programs using one goroutine per processor core.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] The expert's programs were usually faster, but also longer.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Go's approach to concurrency can be summarized as "don't communicate by sharing memory; share memory by communicating".
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] There are no restrictions on how goroutines access shared data, making data races possible.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Specifically, unless a program explicitly synchronizes via channels or other means, writes from one goroutine might be partly, entirely, or not at all visible to another, often with no guarantees about ordering of writes.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Furthermore, Go's *internal data structures* like interface values, slice headers, hash tables, and string headers are not immune to data races, so type and memory safety can be violated in multithreaded programs that modify shared instances of those types without synchronization.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Instead of language support, safe concurrent programming thus relies on conventions; for example, Chisnall recommends an idiom called "aliases xor mutable", meaning that passing a mutable value (or pointer) over a channel signals a transfer of ownership over the value to its receiver.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] The gc toolchain has an optional data race detector that can check for unsynchronized access to shared memory during runtime since version 1.1, additionally a best-effort race detector is also included by default since version 1.6 of the gc runtime for access to the `map` data type.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] The linker in the gc toolchain creates statically linked binaries by default; therefore all Go binaries include the Go runtime.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Go deliberately omits certain features common in other languages, including (implementation) inheritance, assertions, pointer arithmetic, implicit type conversions, untagged unions, and tagged unions.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] The designers added only those facilities that all three agreed on.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Of the omitted language features, the designers explicitly argue against assertions and pointer arithmetic, while defending the choice to omit type inheritance as giving a more useful language, encouraging instead the use of interfaces to achieve dynamic dispatch and composition to reuse code.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Exception handling was initially omitted in Go due to lack of a "design that gives value proportionate to the complexity".
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] An exception-like `panic`/`recover` mechanism that avoids the usual `try-catch` control structure was proposed and released in the March 30, 2010 snapshot.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] The Go authors advise using it for unrecoverable errors such as those that should halt an entire program or server request, or as a shortcut to propagate errors up the stack within a package.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Across package boundaries, Go includes a canonical error type, and multi-value returns using this type are the standard idiom.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] It also includes profiling and debugging support, fuzzing capabilities to detect bugs, runtime instrumentation (for example, to track garbage collection pauses), and a data race detector.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Another tool maintained by the Go team but is not included in Go distributions is `gopls`, a language server that provides IDE features such as intelligent code completion to Language Server Protocol compatible editors.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] An ecosystem of third-party tools adds to the standard distribution, such as `gocode`, which enables code autocompletion in many text editors, `goimports`, which automatically adds/removes package imports as needed, and `errcheck`, which detects code that might unintentionally ignore errors.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] where "fmt" is the package for *formatted I/O*, similar to C's <stdio.h> or C++ <print>.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] The following simple program demonstrates Go's concurrency features to implement an asynchronous program.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] It launches two lightweight threads ("goroutines"): one waits for the user to type some text, while the other implements a timeout.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] The select statement waits for either of these goroutines to send a message to the main routine, and acts on the first message to arrive (example adapted from David Chisnall's book).
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] The testing package provides support for automated testing of go packages.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] It is possible to run tests in parallel.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] The net/http package provides support for creating web applications.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] This example would show "Hello world!" when localhost:8080 is visited.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Go has found widespread adoption in various domains due to its robust standard library and ease of use.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] The interface system, and the deliberate omission of inheritance, were praised by Michele Simionato, who likened these characteristics to those of Standard ML, calling it "a shame that no popular language has followed [this] particular route".
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] By June 2015, its ranking had dropped to below 50th in the index, placing it lower than COBOL and Fortran.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] But as of January 2017, its ranking had surged to 13th, indicating significant growth in popularity and adoption.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] Go was again awarded TIOBE Programming Language of the Year in 2016.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] The evaluation got a rebuttal from the Go development team.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/go-programming-language] On November 10, 2009, the day of the general release of the language, Francis McCabe, developer of the Go! programming language (note the exclamation point), requested a name change of Google's language to prevent confusion with his language, which he had spent 10 years developing.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] A **hypervisor**, also known as a **virtual machine monitor** (**VMM**), is a type of computer software, firmware or hardware that creates and runs virtual machines.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] A computer on which a hypervisor runs one or more virtual machines is called a *host machine* or *virtualization server*, and each virtual machine is called a *guest machine*.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] The hypervisor presents the guest operating systems with a virtual operating platform and manages the execution of the guest operating systems.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] Unlike an emulator, the guest executes most instructions on the native hardware.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] Multiple instances of a variety of operating systems may share the virtualized hardware resources: for example, Linux, Windows, and macOS instances can all run on a single physical x86 machine.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] This contrasts with operating system-level virtualization, where all instances (usually called *containers*) must share a single kernel, though the guest operating systems can differ in user space, such as different Linux distributions with the same kernel.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] The term *hypervisor* is a variant of *supervisor*, a traditional term for the kernel of an operating system: the hypervisor is the supervisor of the supervisors, with *hyper-* used as a stronger variant of *super-*.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] The term dates to circa 1970; IBM coined it for software that ran OS/360 and the 7090 emulator concurrently on the 360/65 and later used it for the DIAG handler of CP-67.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] In the earlier CP/CMS (1967) system, the term *Control Program* was used instead.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] Some literature, especially in microkernel contexts, makes a distinction between *hypervisor* and *virtual machine monitor* (*VMM*).
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] There, both components form the overall *virtualization stack* of a certain system.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] *Hypervisor* refers to kernel-space functionality and VMM to user-space functionality.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] Specifically in these contexts, a *hypervisor* is a microkernel implementing virtualization infrastructure that must run in kernel-space for technical reasons, such as Intel VMX.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] Microkernels implementing virtualization mechanisms are also referred to as *microhypervisor*.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] Applying this terminology to Linux, KVM is a *hypervisor* and QEMU or Cloud Hypervisor are VMMs utilizing KVM as hypervisor.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] In his 1973 thesis *Architectural Principles for Virtual Computer Systems*, Robert P.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] These hypervisors run directly on the host's hardware to control the hardware and to manage guest operating systems.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] The first hypervisors, which IBM developed in the 1960s, were native hypervisors.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] These hypervisors run on a conventional operating system (OS) just as other computer programs do.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] Type-2 hypervisors abstract guest operating systems from the host operating system, effectively creating an isolated system that can be interacted with by the host.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] The distinction between these two types is not always clear.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] For instance, KVM and bhyve are kernel modules that effectively convert the host operating system to a type-1 hypervisor.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] The first hypervisors providing full virtualization were the test tool SIMMON and the one-off IBM CP-40 research system, which began production use in January 1967 and became the first version of the IBM CP/CMS operating system.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] CP-40 ran on a S/360-40 modified at the Cambridge Scientific Center to support dynamic address translation, a feature that enabled virtualization.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] Prior to this time, computer hardware had only been virtualized to the extent to allow multiple user applications to run concurrently, such as in CTSS and IBM M44/44X.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] With CP-40, the hardware's *supervisor state* was virtualized as well, allowing multiple operating systems to run concurrently in separate virtual machine contexts.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] Programmers soon implemented CP-40 (as CP-67) for the IBM System/360-67, the first production computer system capable of full virtualization.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] IBM shipped this machine in 1966; it included page-translation-table hardware for virtual memory and other techniques that allowed a full virtualization of all kernel tasks, including I/O and interrupt handling.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] (The "official" operating system, the ill-fated TSS/360, did not employ full virtualization.) Both CP-40 and CP-67 began production use in 1967.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] CP/CMS was available to IBM customers from 1968 to early 1970s, in source code form without support.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] CP/CMS formed part of IBM's attempt to build robust time-sharing systems for its mainframe computers.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] By running multiple operating systems concurrently, the hypervisor increased system robustness and stability: Even if one operating system crashed, the others would continue working without interruption.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] Indeed, this even allowed beta or experimental versions of operating systems‍—‌or even of new hardware‍—‌to be deployed and debugged, without jeopardizing the stable main production system, and without requiring costly additional development systems.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] IBM announced its System/370 series in 1970 without the virtual memory feature needed for virtualization, but added it in the August 1972 Advanced Function announcement.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] Virtualization has been featured in all successor systems, such that all modern-day IBM mainframes, including the zSeries line, retain backward compatibility with the 1960s-era IBM S/360 line.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] The 1972 announcement also included VM/370, a reimplementation of CP/CMS for the S/370.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] Unlike CP/CMS, IBM provided support for this version (though it was still distributed in source code form for several releases).
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] *VM* stands for *Virtual Machine*, emphasizing that all, not just some, of the hardware interfaces are virtualized.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] Both VM and CP/CMS enjoyed early acceptance and rapid development by universities, corporate users, and time-sharing vendors, as well as within IBM.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] Users played an active role in ongoing development, anticipating trends seen in modern open source projects.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] However, in a series of disputed and bitter battles, time-sharing lost out to batch processing through IBM political infighting, and VM remained IBM's "other" mainframe operating system for decades, losing to MVS.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] It enjoyed a resurgence of popularity and support from 2000 as the z/VM product, for example as the platform for Linux on IBM Z.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] As mentioned above, the VM control program includes a *hypervisor-call* handler that intercepts DIAG ("Diagnose", opcode x'83') instructions used within a virtual machine.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] This provides fast-path non-virtualized execution of file-system access and other operations (DIAG is a model-dependent privileged instruction, not used in normal programming, and thus is not virtualized.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] It is therefore available for use as a signal to the "host" operating system).
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] When first implemented in CP/CMS release 3.1, this use of DIAG provided an operating system interface that was analogous to the System/360 Supervisor Call instruction (SVC), but that did not require altering or extending the system's virtualization of SVC.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] In 1985 IBM introduced the PR/SM hypervisor to manage logical partitions (LPAR).
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] Major Unix vendors, including HP, IBM, SGI, and Sun Microsystems, have been selling virtualized hardware since before 2000.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] These have generally been large, expensive systems (in the multimillion-dollar range at the high end), although virtualization has also been available on some low- and mid-range systems, such as IBM pSeries servers, HP Superdome series machines, and Sun/Oracle SPARC T series CoolThreads servers.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] IBM provides virtualization partition technology known as logical partitioning (LPAR) on System/390, zSeries, pSeries and IBM AS/400 systems.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] For IBM's Power Systems, the POWER Hypervisor (PHYP) is a native (bare-metal) hypervisor in firmware and provides isolation between LPARs.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] Processor capacity is provided to LPARs in either a dedicated fashion or on an entitlement basis where unused capacity is harvested and can be re-allocated to busy workloads.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] Groups of LPARs can have their processor capacity managed as if they were in a "pool" - IBM refers to this capability as Multiple Shared-Processor Pools (MSPPs) and implements it in servers with the POWER6 processor.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] LPAR and MSPP capacity allocations can be dynamically changed.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] Memory is allocated to each LPAR (at LPAR initiation or dynamically) and is address-controlled by the POWER Hypervisor.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] For real-mode addressing by operating systems (AIX, Linux, IBM i), the Power processors (POWER4 onwards) have designed virtualization capabilities where a hardware address-offset is evaluated with the OS address-offset to arrive at the physical memory address.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] Input/Output (I/O) adapters can be exclusively "owned" by LPARs or shared by LPARs through an appliance partition known as the Virtual I/O Server (VIOS).
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] HPE provides HP Integrity Virtual Machines (Integrity VM) to host multiple operating systems on their Itanium powered Integrity systems.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] Itanium can run HP-UX, Linux, Windows and OpenVMS, and these environments are also supported as virtual servers on HP's Integrity VM platform.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] While it heavily leverages HP-UX, the Integrity VM hypervisor is really a hybrid that runs on bare-metal while guests are executing.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] Running normal HP-UX applications on an Integrity VM host is heavily discouraged, because Integrity VM implements its own memory management, scheduling and I/O policies that are tuned for virtual machines and are not as effective for normal applications.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] HPE also provides more rigid partitioning of their Integrity and HP9000 systems by way of VPAR and nPar technology, the former offering shared resource partitioning and the latter offering complete I/O and processing isolation.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] The flexibility of virtual server environment (VSE) has given way to its use more frequently in newer deployments.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] Wind River "Carrier Grade Linux" also runs on Sun's Hypervisor.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] Full virtualization on SPARC processors proved straightforward: since its inception in the mid-1980s Sun deliberately kept the SPARC architecture clean of artifacts that would have impeded virtualization.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] Similar trends have occurred with x86/x86-64 server platforms, where open-source projects such as Xen have led virtualization efforts.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] These include hypervisors built on Linux and Solaris kernels as well as custom kernels.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] Since these technologies span from large systems down to desktops, they are described in the next section.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] x86 virtualization was introduced in the 1990s, with its emulation being included in Bochs.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] Intel and AMD released their first x86 processors with hardware virtualisation in 2005 with Intel VT-x (code-named Vanderpool) and AMD-V (code-named Pacifica).
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] An alternative approach requires modifying the guest operating system to make a system call to the underlying hypervisor, rather than executing machine I/O instructions that the hypervisor simulates.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] This is called paravirtualization in Xen, a "hypercall" in Parallels Workstation, and a "DIAGNOSE code" in IBM VM.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] Some microkernels, such as Mach and L4, are flexible enough to allow paravirtualization of guest operating systems.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] Embedded hypervisors, targeting embedded systems and certain real-time operating system (RTOS) environments, are designed with different requirements when compared to desktop and enterprise systems, including robustness, security and real-time capabilities.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] The resource-constrained nature of multiple embedded systems, especially battery-powered mobile systems, imposes a further requirement for small memory-size and low overhead.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] Finally, in contrast to the ubiquity of the x86 architecture in the PC world, the embedded world uses a wider variety of architectures and less standardized environments.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] Support for virtualization requires memory protection (in the form of a memory management unit or at least a memory protection unit) and a distinction between user mode and privileged mode, which rules out most microcontrollers.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] This still leaves x86, MIPS, ARM and PowerPC as widely deployed architectures on medium- to high-end embedded systems.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] As manufacturers of embedded systems usually have the source code to their operating systems, they have less need for full virtualization in this space.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] Instead, the performance advantages of paravirtualization make this usually the virtualization technology of choice.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] Nevertheless, ARM and MIPS have recently added full virtualization support as an IP option and has included it in their latest high-end processors and architecture versions, such as ARM Cortex-A15 MPCore and ARMv8 EL2.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] Implementation of the concept has allegedly occurred in the SubVirt laboratory rootkit (developed jointly by Microsoft and University of Michigan researchers) as well as in the Blue Pill malware package.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] However, such assertions have been disputed by others who claim that it would be possible to detect the presence of a hypervisor-based rootkit.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/hypervisor] In 2009, researchers from Microsoft and North Carolina State University demonstrated a hypervisor-layer anti-rootkit called Hooksafe that can provide generic protection against kernel-mode rootkits.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] A **kernel** is a computer program at the core of a computer's operating system that always has complete control over everything in the system.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel is also responsible for preventing and mitigating conflicts between different processes.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] It is the portion of the operating system that is always resident in memory and facilitates interactions between hardware and software components.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] A full kernel controls all hardware resources (e.g.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] I/O, memory, cryptography) via device drivers, arbitrates conflicts between processes concerning such resources, and optimizes the use of common resources, such as CPU, cache, file systems, and network sockets.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] On most systems, the kernel is one of the first programs loaded on startup (after the bootloader).
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] It handles the rest of startup as well as memory, peripherals, and input/output (I/O) requests from software, translating them into data-processing instructions for the central processing unit.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] The critical code of the kernel is usually loaded into a separate area of memory, which is protected from access by application software or other less critical parts of the operating system.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel performs its tasks, such as scheduling processes, managing hardware devices such as the hard disk, and handling interrupts, in this protected kernel space.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] In contrast, application programs such as browsers, word processors, or audio or video players use a separate area of memory, user space.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] This prevents user data and kernel data from interfering with each other and causing instability and slowness, as well as preventing malfunctioning applications from affecting other applications or crashing the entire operating system.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Even in systems where the kernel is included in application address spaces, memory protection is used to prevent unauthorized applications from modifying the kernel.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel's interface is a low-level abstraction layer.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] When a process requests a service from the kernel, it must invoke a system call, usually through a wrapper function.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] There are different kernel architecture designs.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Monolithic kernels run entirely in a single address space with the CPU executing in supervisor mode, mainly for speed.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Microkernels run most but not all of their services in user space, like user processes do, mainly for resilience and modularity.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] MINIX 3 is a notable example of microkernel design.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Some kernels, such as the Linux kernel, are both monolithic and modular, since they can insert and remove loadable kernel modules at runtime.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] This central component of a computer system is responsible for executing programs.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel takes responsibility for deciding at any time which of the many running programs should be allocated to the processor or processors.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Random-access memory (RAM) is used to store both program instructions and data.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Typically, both need to be present in memory for a program to execute.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Often, multiple programs will want memory access, frequently demanding more memory than the computer has available.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel is responsible for deciding which memory each process can use, and determining what to do when insufficient memory is available.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] I/O devices include, but are not limited to, peripherals such as keyboards, mice, disk drives, printers, USB devices, network adapters, and display devices.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel provides convenient methods for applications to use these devices, which are typically abstracted by the kernel so that applications do not need to know their implementation details.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Key aspects necessary in resource management are defining the execution domain (address space) and the protection mechanism used to mediate access to the resources within a domain.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Kernels also provide methods for synchronization and inter-process communication (IPC).
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] These implementations may be located within the kernel itself or the kernel can also rely on other processes it is running.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Although the kernel must provide IPC in order to provide access to the facilities provided by each other, kernels must also provide running programs with a method to make requests to access these facilities.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel is also responsible for context switching between processes or threads.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel has full access to the system's memory and must allow processes to safely access this memory as they require it.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Often the first step in doing this is virtual addressing, usually achieved by paging and/or segmentation.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Virtual addressing allows the kernel to make a given physical address appear to be another address, the virtual address.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Virtual address spaces may be different for different processes; the memory that one process accesses at a particular (virtual) address may be different memory from what another process accesses at the same address.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] This allows every program to behave as if it is the only one (apart from the kernel) running and thus prevents applications from crashing each other.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] On many systems, a program's virtual address may refer to data that is not currently in memory.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] The layer of indirection provided by virtual addressing allows the operating system to use other data stores, like a hard drive, to store what would otherwise have to remain in main memory (RAM).
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] As a result, operating systems can allow programs to use more memory than the system has physically available.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] When a program needs data that is not currently in RAM, the CPU signals to the kernel that this has happened, and the kernel responds by writing the contents of an inactive memory block to disk (if necessary) and replacing it with the data requested by the program.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] The program can then be resumed from the point where it was stopped.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] This scheme is generally known as demand paging.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Virtual addressing also allows creation of virtual partitions of memory in two disjoint areas, one being reserved for the kernel (kernel space) and the other for the applications (user space).
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] The applications are not permitted by the processor to address kernel memory, thus preventing an application from damaging the running kernel.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] This fundamental partition of memory space has contributed much to the current designs of actual general-purpose kernels and is almost universal in such systems, although some research kernels (e.g., Singularity) take other approaches.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] To perform useful functions, processes need access to the peripherals connected to the computer, which are controlled by the kernel through device drivers.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] A device driver is a computer program encapsulating, monitoring and controlling a hardware device (via its hardware/software interface (HSI)) on behalf of the OS.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] It provides the operating system with an API, procedures and information about how to control and communicate with a certain piece of hardware.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Device drivers are an important and vital dependency for all OS and their applications.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] The design goal of a driver is abstraction; the function of the driver is to translate the OS-mandated abstract function calls (programming calls) into device-specific calls.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] In theory, a device should work correctly with a suitable driver.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Device drivers are used for e.g. host adapters, video cards, sound cards, printers, scanners, modems, and network interface controllers.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] For example, to show the user something on the screen, an application would make a request to the kernel, which would forward the request to its display driver, which is then responsible for actually plotting the character/pixel.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] A kernel must maintain a list of available devices.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] In plug-and-play systems, a device manager first performs a scan on different peripheral buses, such as Peripheral Component Interconnect (PCI) or Universal Serial Bus (USB), to detect installed devices, then searches for the appropriate drivers.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] As device management is a very OS-specific topic, these drivers are handled differently by each kind of kernel design, but in every case, the kernel has to provide the I/O to allow drivers to physically access their devices through some port or memory location.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Important decisions have to be made when designing the device management system, as in some designs accesses may involve context switches, making the operation very CPU-intensive and easily causing a significant performance overhead.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] In computing, a system call is how a process requests a service from an operating system's kernel that it does not normally have permission to run.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] System calls provide the interface between a process and the operating system.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Most operations interacting with the system require permissions not available to a user-level process, e.g., I/O performed with a device present on the system, or any form of communication with other processes requires the use of system calls.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] A system call is a mechanism that is used by the application program to request a service from the operating system.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] They use a machine-code instruction that causes the processor to change mode.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] An example would be from supervisor mode to protected mode.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] This is where the operating system performs actions like accessing hardware devices or the memory management unit.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Generally the operating system provides a library that sits between the operating system and normal user programs.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Usually it is a C library such as Glibc or Windows API.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] The library handles the low-level details of passing information to the kernel and switching to supervisor mode.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] System calls include close, open, read, wait and write.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] To actually perform useful work, a process must be able to access the services provided by the kernel.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] This is implemented differently by each kernel, but most provide a C library or an API, which in turn invokes the related kernel functions.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] The method of invoking the kernel function varies from kernel to kernel.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] If memory isolation is in use, it is impossible for a user process to call the kernel directly, because that would be a violation of the processor's access control rules.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] An important consideration in the design of a kernel is the support it provides for protection from faults (fault tolerance) and from malicious behaviours (security).
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] These two aspects are usually not clearly distinguished, and the adoption of this distinction in the kernel design leads to the rejection of a hierarchical structure for protection.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Support for hierarchical protection domains is typically implemented using CPU modes.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Many kernels implement "capabilities", i.e., objects provided to user code that allow limited access to an underlying object managed by the kernel.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] A common example is file handling: a file is a representation of information stored on a permanent storage device.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel may be able to perform many different operations, including read, write, delete or execute, but a user-level application may only be permitted to perform some of these operations (e.g., it may only be allowed to read the file).
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] A common implementation of this is for the kernel to provide an object to the application (typically called a "file handle") that the application may then invoke operations on, the validity of which the kernel checks at the time the operation is requested.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Such a system may be extended to cover all objects that the kernel manages, and indeed to objects provided by other user applications.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] An efficient and simple way to provide hardware support of capabilities is to delegate to the memory management unit (MMU) the responsibility of checking access-rights for every memory access, a mechanism called capability-based addressing.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Most commercial computer architectures lack such MMU support for capabilities; the Capability Hardware Enhanced RISC Instructions (CHERI) project is developing capability-based mechanisms for several architectures.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] An alternative approach is to simulate capabilities using commonly supported hierarchical domains.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] In this approach, each protected object must reside in an address space that the application does not have access to; the kernel also maintains a list of capabilities in such memory.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] The performance cost of address space switching limits the practicality of this approach in systems with complex interactions between objects, but it is used in current operating systems for objects that are not accessed frequently or that are not expected to perform quickly.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] If the firmware does not support protection mechanisms, it is possible to simulate protection at a higher level, for example by simulating capabilities by manipulating page tables, but there are performance implications.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Lack of hardware support may not be an issue, however, for systems that choose to use language-based protection.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] An important kernel design decision is the choice of the abstraction levels where the security mechanisms and policies should be implemented.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Kernel security mechanisms play a critical role in supporting security at higher levels.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] One approach is to use firmware and kernel support for fault tolerance (see above), and build the security policy for malicious behavior on top of that (adding features such as cryptography mechanisms where necessary), delegating some responsibility to the compiler.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Approaches that delegate enforcement of security policy to the compiler and/or the application level are often called *language-based security*.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] The lack of many critical security mechanisms in current mainstream operating systems impedes the implementation of adequate security policies at the application abstraction level.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] In fact, a common misconception in computer security is that any security policy can be implemented in an application regardless of kernel support.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] According to Mars Research Group developers, a lack of isolation is one of the main factors undermining kernel security.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] They propose their driver isolation framework for protection, primarily in the Linux kernel.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Typical computer systems today use hardware-enforced rules about what programs are allowed to access what data.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] The processor monitors the execution and stops a program that violates a rule, such as a user process that tries to write to kernel memory.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] In systems that lack support for capabilities, processes are isolated from each other by using separate address spaces.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Calls from user processes into the kernel are regulated by requiring them to use one of the above-described system call methods.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] An alternative approach is to use language-based protection.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] In a language-based protection system, the kernel will only allow code to execute that has been produced by a trusted language compiler.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] The language may then be designed such that it is impossible for the programmer to instruct it to do something that will violate a security requirement.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Examples of systems with language-based protection include JX and Microsoft's Singularity.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Edsger Dijkstra proved that from a logical point of view, atomic lock and unlock operations operating on binary semaphores are sufficient primitives to express any functionality of process cooperation.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Nonetheless, this approach is generally held to be lacking in terms of safety and efficiency, whereas a message passing approach is more flexible.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] A number of other approaches (either lower- or higher-level) are available as well, with many modern kernels providing support for systems such as shared memory and remote procedure calls.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] The idea of a kernel where I/O devices are handled uniformly with other processes, as parallel co-operating processes, was first proposed and implemented by Brinch Hansen (although similar ideas were suggested in 1967).
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] In Hansen's description of this, the "common" processes are called *internal processes*, while the I/O devices are called *external processes*.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Similar to physical memory, allowing applications direct access to controller ports and registers can cause the controller to malfunction, or system to crash.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] With this, depending on the complexity of the device, some devices can get surprisingly complex to program, and use several different controllers.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Because of this, providing a more abstract interface to manage the device is important.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] This interface is normally done by a device driver or hardware abstraction layer.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Frequently, applications will require access to these devices.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel must maintain the list of these devices by querying the system for them in some way.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] This can be done through the BIOS, or through one of the various system buses (such as PCI/PCIE, or USB).
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Using an example of a video driver, when an application requests an operation on a device, such as displaying a character, the kernel needs to send this request to the current active video driver.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] The video driver, in turn, needs to carry out this request.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] This is an example of inter-process communication (IPC).
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] The above listed tasks and features can be provided in many ways that differ from each other in design and implementation.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] The principle of *separation of mechanism and policy* is the substantial difference between the two main philosophies of microkernels and monolithic kernels.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Here a *mechanism* is the support that allows the implementation of many different policies, while a *policy* is a particular "mode of operation".
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Because the mechanism and policy are separated, the policy can be easily changed to, e.g., require the use of a security token.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] A monolithic kernel instead tends to include many policies, therefore restricting the rest of the system to rely on them.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Computer scientist Per Brinch Hansen argued in favour of separation of mechanism and policy.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] The failure to properly fulfill this separation is one of the major causes of the lack of substantial innovation in existing operating systems, a problem common in computer architecture.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] The monolithic design is induced by the "kernel mode"/"user mode" architectural approach to protection (technically called hierarchical protection domains), which is common in conventional commercial systems; in fact, every module needing protection is therefore preferably included into the kernel.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] While monolithic kernels execute all of their code in the same address space (kernel space), microkernels try to run most of their services in user space, aiming to improve maintainability and modularity of their codebase.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Most kernels do not fit exactly into one of these categories, but are rather found in between these two designs.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] More exotic designs such as nanokernels and exokernels are available, but are seldom used for production systems.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] The Xen hypervisor, for example, is an exokernel.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] In a monolithic kernel, all OS services are part of the kernel and run in kernel mode, thus also residing in the same memory area.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] This approach provides rich and powerful hardware access.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] UNIX developer Ken Thompson stated that "it is in [his] opinion easier to implement a monolithic kernel".
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] The main disadvantages of monolithic kernels are the dependencies between system components – a bug in a device driver might crash the entire system, for example – and the fact that large kernels can become very difficult to maintain.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Thompson also stated that "It is also easier for [a monolithic kernel] to turn into a mess in a hurry as it is modified".
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Monolithic kernels, which have traditionally been used by Unix-like operating systems, contain all the operating system core functions and the device drivers.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] A monolithic kernel is one single program that contains all of the code necessary to perform every kernel-related task.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Every part that is to be accessed by a program that cannot be put in a library is in the kernel space, including drivers, schedulers, memory management, file systems, and network stacks.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Many system calls are provided to applications, to allow them to access all those services.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] A monolithic kernel, while initially loaded with subsystems that may not be needed, can be tuned to a point where it is as fast as or faster than one that was specifically designed for the hardware, although more relevant in a general sense.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Most work in the monolithic kernel is done via system calls.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] These are interfaces, usually kept in a tabular structure, that access some subsystem within the kernel, such as disk operations.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Essentially, calls are made within programs and a checked copy of the request is passed through the system call.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] The monolithic Linux kernel can be made extremely small not only because of its ability to dynamically load modules but also because of its ease of customization.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] In fact, there are some versions that are small enough to fit together with a large number of utilities and other programs on a single floppy disk and still provide a fully functional operating system (one of the most popular of which is muLinux).
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] This ability to miniaturize its kernel has also led to a rapid growth in the use of Linux in embedded systems.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] These types of kernels consist of the core functions of the operating system and the device drivers with the ability to load modules at runtime.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] They provide rich and powerful abstractions of the underlying hardware.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] They provide a small set of simple hardware abstractions and use applications called servers to provide more functionality.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] This particular approach defines a high-level virtual interface over the hardware, with a set of system calls to implement operating system services such as process management, concurrency and memory management in several modules that run in supervisor mode.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] A microkernel that is designed for a specific platform or device is only ever going to have what it needs to operate.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] The microkernel approach consists of defining a simple abstraction over the hardware, with a set of primitives or system calls to implement minimal OS services such as memory management, multitasking, and inter-process communication.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Other services, including those normally provided by the kernel, such as networking, are implemented in user-space programs, referred to as *servers*.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Microkernels are easier to maintain than monolithic kernels, but the large number of system calls and context switches might slow down the system because they typically generate more overhead than plain function calls.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Only parts that really require being in a privileged mode are in kernel space, such as IPC (Inter-Process Communication), a basic scheduler or scheduling primitives, basic memory handling, and basic I/O primitives.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Many critical parts are now running in user space, including the complete scheduler, memory handling, file systems, and network stacks.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Microkernels were invented as a reaction to traditional "monolithic" kernel design, whereby all system functionality was put in one static program running in a special "system" mode of the processor.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] In the microkernel, only the most fundamental of tasks are performed at this level, such as being able to access some (not necessarily all) of the hardware, manage memory and coordinate message passing between the processes.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Some systems that use microkernels are QNX and GNU Hurd.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] In the case of QNX and GNU Hurd, user sessions can be entire snapshots of the system itself, or "views" as it is referred to.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Most microkernels use a message passing system to handle requests from one server to another.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] The message passing system generally operates on a port basis with the microkernel.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] As an example, if a request for more memory is sent, a port is opened with the microkernel and the request sent through.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Once within the microkernel, the steps are similar to system calls.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] The rationale was that it would bring modularity in the system architecture, which would entail a cleaner system that is easier to debug or dynamically modify, customizable to users' needs, and higher performing.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Microkernels are part of operating systems like GNU Hurd, MINIX, MkLinux, QNX and Redox OS.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Although microkernels are very small by themselves, in combination with all their required auxiliary code they are, in fact, often larger than monolithic kernels.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Advocates of monolithic kernels also point out that the two-tiered structure of microkernel systems, in which most of the operating system does not interact directly with the hardware, creates a not-insignificant cost in terms of system efficiency.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] These types of kernels normally provide only the minimal services such as defining memory address spaces, inter-process communication (IPC) and process management.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Other functions, such as running hardware processes, are not handled directly by microkernels.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Proponents of microkernels point out those monolithic kernels have the disadvantage that an error in the kernel can cause the entire system to crash.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] With a microkernel, however, if a kernel process crashes, it is still possible to prevent a crash of the system as a whole by merely restarting the service that caused the error.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Other services provided by the kernel such as networking are implemented in user-space programs referred to as *servers*.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Servers allow the operating system to be modified by simply starting and stopping programs.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] For a machine without networking support, for instance, the networking server is not started.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] The task of moving in and out of the kernel to move data between the various applications and servers creates overhead that is detrimental to the efficiency of microkernels in comparison with monolithic kernels.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Disadvantages in the microkernel exist, however.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] The disadvantages for microkernels are extremely context-based.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] As an example, they work well for small single-purpose (and critical) systems because if not many processes need to run, then the complications of process management are effectively mitigated.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] A microkernel allows the implementation of the remaining part of the operating system as programs running in user mode, and the use of different operating systems on top of the same unchanged kernel.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] It is also possible to dynamically switch among operating systems and to have more than one active simultaneously.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] As the computer kernel grows, so grows the size and vulnerability of its trusted computing base, in addition to its memory footprint.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] This is mitigated to some degree by perfecting a virtual memory system, but not all computer architectures have virtual memory support.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] To reduce the kernel's footprint, extensive editing has to be performed to carefully remove unneeded code, which can be very difficult with non-obvious interdependencies between parts of a kernel with millions of lines of code.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] By the early 1990s, due to the various shortcomings of monolithic kernels versus microkernels, monolithic kernels were considered obsolete by virtually all operating system researchers.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] As a result, the design of Linux as a monolithic kernel rather than a microkernel was the topic of a famous debate between Linus Torvalds and Andrew Tanenbaum.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] There is merit on both sides of the argument presented in the Tanenbaum–Torvalds debate.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Monolithic kernels are designed to have all of their code in the same address space (kernel space), which some developers argue is necessary to increase the performance of the system.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Some developers also maintain that monolithic systems are extremely efficient if well written.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] The monolithic model tends to be more efficient through the use of shared kernel memory, rather than the slower IPC system of microkernel designs, which is typically based on message passing.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] The performance of microkernels was poor in both the 1980s and early 1990s.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Studies that empirically measured the performance of these microkernels did not analyze the reasons of such inefficiency.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] The explanations of this data were left to "folklore", with the assumption that they were due to the increased frequency of switches from "kernel-mode" to "user-mode", to the increased frequency of inter-process communication and to the increased frequency of context switches.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] In fact, as guessed in 1995, the reasons for the poor performance of microkernels might as well have been: (1) an actual inefficiency of the whole microkernel *approach*, (2) the particular *concepts* implemented in those microkernels, and (3) the particular *implementation* of those concepts.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Therefore it remained to be studied if the solution to build an efficient microkernel was, unlike previous attempts, to apply the correct construction techniques.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Hybrid kernels are used in some commercial operating systems, including most versions of Microsoft Windows to date (NT 3.1, NT 3.5, NT 3.51, NT 4.0, 2000, XP, Vista, 7, 8, 8.1, 10 and 11).
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Apple's macOS uses a hybrid kernel called XNU, which is based upon code from OSF/1's Mach kernel (OSFMK 7.3) and FreeBSD's monolithic kernel.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Hybrid kernels are similar to microkernels, except they include some additional code in kernel-space to increase performance.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] These kernels represent a compromise that was implemented by some developers to accommodate the major advantages of both monolithic and microkernels.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] These types of kernels are extensions of microkernels with some properties of monolithic kernels.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Unlike monolithic kernels, these types of kernels are unable to load modules at runtime on their own.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] This implies running some services (such as the network stack or the filesystem) in kernel space to reduce the performance overhead of a traditional microkernel, but still running kernel code (such as device drivers) as servers in user space.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Many traditionally monolithic kernels support loadable kernel modules.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] The most well known of these kernels is the Linux kernel.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] The modular kernel essentially can have parts of it that are built into the core kernel binary or binaries that load into memory on demand.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] A code-tainted module has the potential to destabilize a running kernel.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] By contrast, it is possible to write a driver for a microkernel in a completely separate memory space and test it before "going" live.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] When a kernel module is loaded, it accesses the monolithic portion's memory space by adding to it what it needs, therefore opening the doorway to possible pollution.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Modules, generally, communicate with the kernel using a module interface of some sort.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] The interface is generalized (although particular to a given operating system) so it is not always possible to use modules.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Often the device drivers may need more flexibility than the module interface affords.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Essentially, it is two system calls and often the safety checks that only have to be done once in the monolithic kernel now may be done twice.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] A nanokernel delegates virtually all services – including even the most basic ones like interrupt controllers or the timer – to device drivers to make the kernel memory requirement even smaller than a traditional microkernel.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Exokernels are a still-experimental approach to operating system design.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] They differ from other types of kernels in limiting their functionality to the protection of and multiplexing of access to the raw hardware, providing no hardware abstractions on top of which to develop applications.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] This separation of hardware protection from hardware management enables application developers to determine how to make the most efficient use of the available hardware for each specific program.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Exokernels in themselves are extremely small.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Nonetheless, they are accompanied by library operating systems (see also unikernel), providing application developers with the functionalities of a conventional operating system.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] A major advantage of exokernel-based systems is that they can incorporate multiple library operating systems, each exporting a different API, for example one for high level UI development and one for real-time control.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] A multikernel operating system treats a multi-core machine as a network of independent cores, as if it were a distributed system.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] It does not assume shared memory but rather implements inter-process communications as message passing.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p01] Barrelfish was the first operating system to be described as a multikernel.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] Strictly speaking, an operating system (and thus, a kernel) is not *required* to run a computer.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] Programs can be directly loaded and executed on the "bare metal" machine, provided that the authors of those programs are willing to work without any hardware abstraction or operating system support.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] Most early computers operated this way during the 1950s and early 1960s, which were reset and reloaded between the execution of different programs.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] Eventually, small ancillary programs such as program loaders and debuggers were left in memory between runs, or loaded from ROM.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] As these were developed, they formed the basis of what became early operating system kernels.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] The "bare metal" approach is still used today on some video game consoles and embedded systems, but in general, newer computers use modern operating systems and kernels.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] In 1969, the RC 4000 Multiprogramming System introduced the system design philosophy of a small nucleus "upon which operating systems for different purposes could be built in an orderly manner", what would be called the microkernel approach.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] In the decade preceding Unix, computers had grown enormously in power – to the point where computer operators were looking for new ways to get people to use their spare time on their machines.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] One of the major developments during this era was time-sharing, whereby a number of users would get small slices of computer time, at a rate at which it appeared they were each connected to their own, slower, machine.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] The development of time-sharing systems led to a number of problems.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] One was that users, particularly at universities where the systems were being developed, wanted to hack the system to get more CPU time.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] For this reason, security and access control became a major focus of the Multics project in 1965.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] Another ongoing issue was properly handling computing resources: users spent most of their time staring at the terminal and thinking about what to input instead of actually using the resources of the computer, and a time-sharing system should give the CPU time to an active user during these periods.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] Finally, the systems typically offered a memory hierarchy several layers deep, and partitioning this expensive resource led to major developments in virtual memory systems.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] The Commodore Amiga was released in 1985, and was among the first – and certainly most successful – home computers to feature an advanced kernel architecture.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] The AmigaOS kernel's executive component, *exec.library*, uses a microkernel message-passing design, but there are other kernel components, like *graphics.library*, that have direct access to the hardware.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] There is no memory protection, and the kernel is almost always running in user mode.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] Only special actions are executed in kernel mode, and user-mode applications can ask the operating system to execute their code in kernel mode.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] During the design phase of Unix, programmers decided to model every high-level device as a file, because they believed the purpose of computation was data transformation.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] For instance, printers were represented as a "file" at a known location – when data was copied to the file, it printed out.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] Other systems, to provide a similar functionality, tended to virtualize devices at a lower level – that is, both devices *and* files would be instances of some lower level concept.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] Virtualizing the system at the file level allowed users to manipulate the entire system using their existing file management utilities and concepts, dramatically simplifying operation.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] As an extension of the same paradigm, Unix allows programmers to manipulate files using a series of small programs, using the concept of pipes, which allowed users to complete operations in stages, feeding a file through a chain of single-purpose tools.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] Although the end result was the same, using smaller programs in this way dramatically increased flexibility as well as ease of development and use, allowing the user to modify their workflow by adding or removing a program from the chain.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] In the Unix model, the *operating system* consists of two parts: first, the huge collection of utility programs that drive most operations; second, the kernel that runs the programs.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] Over the years the computing model changed, and Unix's treatment of everything as a file or byte stream no longer was as universally applicable as it was before.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] Although a terminal could be treated as a file or a byte stream, which is printed to or read from, the same did not seem to be true for a graphical user interface.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] Even if network communication can be compared to file access, the low-level packet-oriented architecture dealt with discrete chunks of data and not with whole files.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] As the capability of computers grew, Unix became increasingly cluttered with code.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] It is also because the modularity of the Unix kernel is extensively scalable.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] While kernels might have had 100,000 lines of code in the seventies and eighties, kernels like Linux, of modern Unix successors like GNU, have more than 13 million lines.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] Modern Unix-derivatives are generally based on module-loading monolithic kernels.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] Examples of this are the Linux kernel in the many distributions of GNU, IBM AIX, as well as the Berkeley Software Distribution variant kernels such as FreeBSD, DragonFly BSD, OpenBSD, NetBSD, and macOS.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] Apart from these alternatives, amateur developers maintain an active operating system development community, populated by self-written hobby kernels that mostly end up sharing many features with Linux, FreeBSD, DragonflyBSD, OpenBSD, or NetBSD kernels and/or being compatible with them.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] Apple first launched its classic Mac OS in 1984, bundled with its Macintosh personal computer.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] Apple moved to a nanokernel design in Mac OS 8.6.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] Against this, the modern macOS (originally named Mac OS X) is based on Darwin, which uses a hybrid kernel called XNU, which was created by combining the 4.3BSD kernel and the Mach kernel.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] Microsoft Windows was first released in 1985 as an add-on to MS-DOS.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] Because of its dependence on another operating system, initial releases of Windows, prior to Windows 95, were considered an operating environment (not to be confused with an operating system).
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] This product line continued to evolve through the 1980s and 1990s, with the Windows 9x series adding 32-bit addressing and pre-emptive multitasking; but ended with the release of Windows Me in 2000.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] Microsoft also developed Windows NT, an operating system with a very similar interface, but intended for high-end and business users.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] This line started with the release of Windows NT 3.1 in 1993, and was introduced to general users with the release of Windows XP in October 2001—replacing Windows 9x with a completely different, much more sophisticated operating system.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] This is the line that continues with Windows 11.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] The architecture of Windows NT's kernel is considered a hybrid kernel because the kernel itself contains tasks such as the Window Manager and the IPC Managers, with a client/server layered subsystem model.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] It was designed as a modified microkernel, as the Windows NT kernel was influenced by the Mach microkernel but does not meet all of the criteria of a pure microkernel.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] Supervisory program or supervisor is a computer program, usually part of an operating system, that controls the execution of other routines and regulates work scheduling, input/output operations, error actions, and similar functions and regulates the flow of work in a data processing system.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] Historically, this term was essentially associated with IBM's line of mainframe operating systems starting with OS/360.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] In other operating systems, the supervisor is generally called the kernel.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] In the 1970s, IBM further abstracted the supervisor state from the hardware, resulting in a hypervisor that enabled full virtualization, i.e. the capacity to run multiple operating systems on the same machine totally independent of each other.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] Hence the first such system was called *Virtual Machine* or *VM*.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] Although Mach, developed by Richard Rashid at Carnegie Mellon University, is the best-known general-purpose microkernel, other microkernels have been developed with more specific aims.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] The L4 microkernel family (mainly the L3 and the L4 kernel) was created to demonstrate that microkernels are not necessarily slow.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] Newer implementations such as Fiasco and Pistachio are able to run Linux next to other L4 processes in separate address spaces.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/kernel-operating-system-p02] Additionally, QNX is a microkernel that is principally used in embedded systems, and the open-source software MINIX, while originally created for educational purposes, is now focused on being a highly reliable and self-healing microkernel OS.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/os-level-virtualization] On Unix-like operating systems, this feature can be seen as an advanced implementation of the standard chroot mechanism, which changes the apparent root folder for the current running process and its children.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/os-level-virtualization] In addition to isolation mechanisms, the kernel often provides resource-management features to limit the impact of one container's activities on other containers.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/os-level-virtualization] Linux containers are all based on the virtualization, isolation, and resource management mechanisms provided by the Linux kernel, notably Linux namespaces and cgroups.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/os-level-virtualization] Although the word *container* most commonly refers to OS-level virtualization, it is sometimes used to refer to fuller virtual machines operating in varying degrees of concert with the host OS, such as Microsoft's Hyper-V containers.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/os-level-virtualization] For an overview of virtualization since 1960, see Timeline of virtualization technologies.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/os-level-virtualization] On ordinary operating systems for personal computers, a computer program can see (even though it might not be able to access) all the system's resources.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/os-level-virtualization] The operating system may allow or deny access to such resources based on which program requests them and the user account in the context in which it runs.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/os-level-virtualization] The operating system may also hide those resources, so that when the computer program enumerates them, they do not appear in the enumeration results.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/os-level-virtualization] Nevertheless, from a programming point of view, the computer program has interacted with those resources and the operating system has managed an act of interaction.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/os-level-virtualization] With operating-system-virtualization, or containerization, it is possible to run programs within containers, to which only parts of these resources are allocated.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/os-level-virtualization] A program expecting to see the whole computer, once run inside a container, can only see the allocated resources and believes them to be all that is available.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/os-level-virtualization] Several containers can be created on each operating system, to each of which a subset of the computer's resources is allocated.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/os-level-virtualization] Each container may contain any number of computer programs.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/os-level-virtualization] These programs may run concurrently or separately, and may even interact with one another.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/os-level-virtualization] Containerization has similarities to application virtualization: In the latter, only one computer program is placed in an isolated container and the isolation applies to file system only.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system level virtualization is commonly used in virtual hosting environments, where it is useful for securely allocating finite hardware resources among a large number of mutually-distrusting users.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/os-level-virtualization] System administrators may also use it for consolidating server hardware by moving services on separate hosts into containers on the one server.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system level virtualization can also be used to run software created for a certain Linux distribution on another distribution, an example is Distrobox.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/os-level-virtualization] Other typical scenarios include separating several programs to separate containers for improved security, hardware independence, and added resource management features.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/os-level-virtualization] The improved security provided by the use of a chroot mechanism, however, is not perfect.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system-level virtualization implementations capable of live migration can also be used for dynamic load balancing of containers between nodes in a cluster.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/os-level-virtualization] This form of virtualization also does not require hardware support for efficient performance.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system level virtualization is not as flexible as other virtualization approaches since it cannot host a guest operating system different from the host one, or a different guest kernel.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/os-level-virtualization] For example, with Linux, different distributions are fine, but other operating systems such as Windows cannot be hosted.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/os-level-virtualization] Operating systems using variable input systematics are subject to limitations within the virtualized architecture.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/os-level-virtualization] Adaptation methods including cloud-server relay analytics maintain the OS-level virtual environment within these applications.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/os-level-virtualization] Solaris partially overcomes the limitation described above with its branded zones feature, which provides the ability to run an environment within a container that emulates an older Solaris 8 or 9 version in a Solaris 10 host.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/os-level-virtualization] However, in 2010 Linux branded zones were removed from Solaris; in 2014 they were reintroduced in Illumos, which is the open source Solaris fork, supporting 32-bit Linux kernels.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/os-level-virtualization] Some implementations provide file-level copy-on-write (CoW) mechanisms.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/os-level-virtualization] (Most commonly, a standard file system is shared between partitions, and those partitions that change the files automatically create their own copies.) This is easier to back up, more space-efficient and simpler to cache than the block-level copy-on-write schemes common on whole-system virtualizers.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/os-level-virtualization] Whole-system virtualizers, however, can work with non-native file systems and create and roll back snapshots of the entire system state.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/sandbox-computer-security] In computer security, a **sandbox** is a security mechanism for separating running programs, usually in an effort to mitigate system failures and/or software vulnerabilities from spreading.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/sandbox-computer-security] The sandbox metaphor derives from the concept of a child's sandbox—a play area where children can build, destroy, and experiment without causing any real-world damage.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/sandbox-computer-security] It is often used to analyze untested or untrusted programs or code, possibly originating from unverified or untrusted third parties, suppliers, users or websites, without risking harm to the host machine or operating system.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/sandbox-computer-security] A sandbox typically provides a tightly controlled set of resources for guest programs to run in, such as storage and memory scratch space.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/sandbox-computer-security] Network access, the ability to inspect the host system, or read from input devices are usually disallowed or heavily restricted.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/sandbox-computer-security] In the sense of providing a highly controlled environment, sandboxing can be comparable to virtualization.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/sandbox-computer-security] Sandboxing is frequently used to test unverified programs that may contain a virus or other malicious code without allowing the software to harm the host device.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/sandbox-computer-security] A sandbox is implemented by executing the software in a restricted operating system environment, thus controlling the resources (e.g. file descriptors, memory, file system space, etc.) that a process may use.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] In computing, a **system call** (**syscall**) is the programmatic way in which a computer program requests a service from the operating system on which it is executed.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] This may include hardware-related services (for example, accessing a hard disk drive or accessing the device's camera), creation and execution of new processes, and communication with integral kernel services such as process scheduling.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] System calls provide an essential interface between a process and the operating system.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] In most systems, system calls can only be made from userspace processes, while in some systems, OS/360 and successors for example, privileged system code also issues system calls.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] For embedded systems, system calls typically do not change the privilege mode of the CPU.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] The architecture of most modern processors, with the exception of some embedded systems, involves a security model.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] However, many applications need access to these components, so system calls are made available by the operating system to provide well-defined, safe implementations for such operations.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] The operating system executes at the highest level of privilege, and allows applications to request services via system calls, which are often initiated via interrupts.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] An interrupt automatically puts the CPU into some elevated privilege level and then passes control to the kernel, which determines whether the calling program should be granted the requested service.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] If the service is granted, the kernel executes a specific set of instructions over which the calling program has no direct control, returns the privilege level to that of the calling program, and then returns control to the calling program.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] Generally, systems provide a library or API that sits between normal programs and the operating system.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] On Unix-like systems, that API is usually part of an implementation of the C library (libc), such as glibc, that provides wrapper functions for the system calls, often named the same as the system calls they invoke.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] On Windows NT, that API is part of the Native API, in the ntdll.dll library; this is an undocumented API used by implementations of the regular Windows API and directly used by some system programs on Windows.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] The library's wrapper functions expose an ordinary function calling convention (a subroutine call on the assembly level) for using the system call, as well as making the system call more modular.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] Here, the primary function of the wrapper is to place all the arguments to be passed to the system call in the appropriate processor registers (and maybe on the call stack as well), and also setting a unique system call number for the kernel to call.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] In this way the library, which exists between the OS and the application, increases portability.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] The call to the library function itself does not cause a switch to kernel mode and is usually a normal subroutine call (using, for example, a "CALL" assembly instruction in some Instruction set architectures (ISAs)).
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] The actual system call does transfer control to the kernel (and is more implementation-dependent and platform-dependent than the library call abstracting it).
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] For example, in Unix-like systems, `fork` and `execve` are C library functions that in turn execute instructions that invoke the `fork` and `exec` system calls.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] On exokernel based systems, the library is especially important as an intermediary.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] On exokernels, libraries shield user applications from the very low level kernel API, and provide abstractions and resource management.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] IBM's OS/360, DOS/360 and TSS/360 implement most system calls through a library of assembly language macros, although there are a few services with a call linkage.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] This reflects their origin at a time when programming in assembly language was more common than high-level language usage.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] IBM system calls were therefore not directly executable by high-level language programs, but required a callable assembly language wrapper subroutine.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] Since then, IBM has added many services that can be called from high level languages in, e.g., z/OS and z/VSE.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] In more recent release of MVS/SP and in all later MVS versions, some system call macros generate Program Call (PC).
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] On Unix, Unix-like and other POSIX-compliant operating systems, popular system calls are `open`, `read`, `write`, `close`, `wait`, `exec`, `fork`, `exit`, and `kill`.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] Many modern operating systems have hundreds of system calls.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] For example, Linux and OpenBSD each have over 300 different calls, NetBSD has close to 500, FreeBSD has over 500, Windows has close to 2000, divided between win32k (graphical) and ntdll (core) system calls while Plan 9 has 54.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] Tools such as strace, ftrace and truss allow a process to execute from start and report all system calls the process invokes, or can attach to an already running process and intercept any system call made by the said process if the operation does not violate the permissions of the user.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] This special ability of the program is usually also implemented with system calls such as ptrace or system calls on files in procfs.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] Implementing system calls requires a transfer of control from user space to kernel space, which involves some sort of architecture-specific feature.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] A typical way to implement this is to use a software interrupt or trap.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] Interrupts transfer control to the operating system kernel, so software simply needs to set up some register with the system call number needed, and execute the software interrupt.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] This is the only technique provided for many RISC processors, but CISC architectures such as x86 support additional techniques.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] For example, the x86 instruction set contains the instructions `SYSCALL`/`SYSRET` and `SYSENTER`/`SYSEXIT` (these two mechanisms were independently created by AMD and Intel, respectively, but in essence they do the same thing).
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] These are "fast" control transfer instructions that are designed to quickly transfer control to the kernel for a system call without the overhead of an interrupt.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] Linux 2.5 began using this on the x86, where available; formerly it used the `INT` instruction, where the system call number was placed in the `EAX` register before interrupt 0x80 was executed.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] An older mechanism is the call gate; originally used in Multics and later, for example, see call gate on the Intel x86.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] It allows a program to call a kernel function directly using a safe control transfer mechanism, which the operating system sets up in advance.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] For IA-64 architecture, `EPC` (Enter Privileged Code) instruction is used.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] The first eight system call arguments are passed in registers, and the rest are passed on the stack.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] In the IBM System/360 mainframe family, and its successors, a Supervisor Call instruction (SVC), with the number in the instruction rather than in a register, implements a system call for legacy facilities in most of IBM's own operating systems, and for all system calls in Linux.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] In later versions of MVS, IBM uses the Program Call (PC) instruction for many newer facilities.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] In particular, PC is used when the caller might be in Service Request Block (SRB) mode.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] The PDP-11 minicomputer used the EMT, TRAP and IOT instructions, which, similar to the IBM System/360 SVC and x86 INT, put the code in the instruction; they generate interrupts to specific addresses, transferring control to the operating system.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] The VAX 32-bit successor to the PDP-11 series used the CHMK, CHME, and CHMS instructions to make system calls to privileged code at various levels; the code is an argument to the instruction.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] Within the RISC-V privileged architecture, the instruction `ECALL` (after *environment call*) is designed to enter a more privileged level and therefore this instruction performs the functionalities related to system calls.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] `ECALL` events are then handled in a similar fashion to other types of synchronous traps, including the same return mechanism.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] In the related Linux implementations, the system call number is placed into the `a7` (`x17`) register before `ECALL` is executed, function arguments are listed in accordance to the RISC-V ABI (`a0`, `a1`, ...) while the return value is put in `a0`.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] System calls in most Unix-like systems are processed in kernel mode, which is accomplished by changing the processor execution mode to a more privileged one, but no *process* context switch is necessary – although a *privilege* context switch does occur.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] The hardware sees the world in terms of the execution mode according to the processor status register, and processes are an abstraction provided by the operating system.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] A system call does not generally require a context switch to another process; instead, it is processed in the context of whichever process invoked it.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] In a multithreaded process, system calls can be made from multiple threads.
[src:gvisor-sandbox/system-call] The handling of such calls is dependent on the design of the specific operating system kernel and the application runtime environment.
